WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.045
Alginate is a sugar from seaweed. On its own it is just

2
00:00:03.145 --> 00:00:06.077
a floppy chain — but add calcium, and it snaps into a

3
00:00:06.177 --> 00:00:08.651
gel. The way it does that has a lovely shape.

4
00:00:09.433 --> 00:00:12.833
Certain stretches of the chain, the G-blocks, are buckled —

5
00:00:12.933 --> 00:00:15.028
and two of them line up face to face.

6
00:00:16.100 --> 00:00:19.232
Between them sit calcium ions, each cradled by the buckles

7
00:00:19.332 --> 00:00:21.964
above and below — exactly like eggs nestled in an

8
00:00:22.064 --> 00:00:24.751
egg carton. Those junctions lock the gel together.

9
00:00:27.233 --> 00:00:30.293
Repeat that junction many times over and the floppy solution

10
00:00:30.393 --> 00:00:33.716
becomes a springy, load-bearing solid that grips the sand grains.

11
00:00:33.800 --> 00:00:37.213
There is an honest catch. Alginate dissolves in water — so every

12
00:00:37.313 --> 00:00:40.288
rain shower washes a little of the gel away. That is why

13
00:00:40.388 --> 00:00:42.868
it is one prong of three, not the whole answer.

